{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_end","contentIndex":2,"toolCall":{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_58387926b13243b3bb847e2a","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record lacks a preserved credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy. The only preserved actual quotations describe future fatherhood aspirations and a pregnancy contest proposal, not confirmation of an existing pregnancy. Forbes presents an incomplete fragment without source chain, while Times of India, Hindustan Times, and Express Tribune report no confirmed pregnancy statement from Clavicular. Under preponderance, the proposition is not demonstrated.\"}"}},"partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I have the opportunity to submit my vote. Let me review the case carefully.\n\nThe proposition is: \"Between market creation on April 20, 2026, and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\"\n\nThe standard of proof is preponderance of the evidence.\n\nLet me analyze the admitted evidence:\n\n**For Plaintiff (demonstrated):**\n1. The Polymarket market rule explicitly allows \"a definitive consensus of credible media reporting\" as a resolution source\n2. Forbes reported the dispute as involving \"a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant\" - this is a direct characterization of an existing pregnancy announcement\n3. The Gamma API shows the market resolved Yes (outcome prices Yes 1 / No 0) after two rounds of proposal and dispute\n4. The market had $13.9M+ volume with sophisticated traders\n\n**For Defendant (not_demonstrated):**\n1. No original livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement is preserved in the record\n2. Times of India fact-check explicitly says: \"no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no video confirming pregnancy, and no statement from Clavicular confirming it\"\n3. Hindustan Times and Express Tribune report the actual preserved words as: \"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months\" - these are future-oriented aspirations, not confirmation of an existing pregnancy\n4. The Forbes extraction itself notes: \"market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.\"\n5. The Forbes extraction is incomplete - just snippets from a paywalled page, not a full article with source chain\n\n**My Analysis:**\n\nThe key issue is whether the evidence proves by preponderance that Clavicular made a *credible announcement* of an *existing pregnancy with a partner*.\n\n\n- Forbes's fragment \"gotten a girl pregnant\" lacks the surrounding context needed to verify whether this was a genuine announcement, rumor, or joke\n- Three adverse sources (TOI, HT, Express Tribune) preserve actual quoted language showing only future intentions and a contest proposal, not confirmation of an existing pregnancy\n- The market's Yes resolution reflects trader consensus, not independent proof that the factual predicate occurred\n- The original source material that would establish credibility is missing from the record\n\nThe defense position seems stronger. The media reports conflict rather than converge, the preserved statements point away from the proposition, and the Forbes snippet alone cannot establish what was actually announced. The proposition requires a credible announcement of an existing pregnancy, but the admitted record shows conflicting media coverage, preserved statements that contradict this, and no primary source material. A final market resolution doesn't establish the underlying fact. I'm voting not_demonstrated.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"I have reviewed the arbitration record and admitted evidence. Let me analyze the key points:\n\n**The Proposition:** Between market creation on April 20, 2026, and December 31, 2026, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\n\n**Key Evidence:**\n\n*For Plaintiff:*\n- Forbes reported the dispute involved \"a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant\"\n- Polymarket market resolved Yes after dispute rounds\n- Market rule allows \"definitive consensus of credible media reporting\"\n\n*For Defendant:*\n- No original livestream, VOD, transcript, or representative statement preserved\n- Times of India: \"no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no video confirming pregnancy, and no statement from Clavicular confirming it\"\n- Hindustan Times and Express Tribune preserve actual quoted words: \"I must have children...I will be a dad in the next few months\" — future aspirations, not existing pregnancy\n- Forbes extraction itself notes: \"market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes.\"\n- Forbes is incomplete snippets from a paywalled page, not full article with source chain\n\n**Analysis:**\nThe admitted record contains conflicting secondary reporting, not a \"definitive consensus.\" The preserved actual quotations describe a pregnancy contest proposal and future fatherhood desires, not confirmation of an existing partner pregnancy. The Forbes fragment lacks context and source chain. A final platform Yes resolution is not independent proof of the factual predicate. The primary source gaps are dispositive under preponderance.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_58387926b13243b3bb847e2a","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record lacks a preserved credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy. The only preserved actual quotations describe future fatherhood aspirations and a pregnancy contest proposal, not confirmation of an e