 Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\n\n**Key Evidence:**\n\n*For Plaintiff:*\n- Forbes reported the dispute involved \"a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant\"\n- Polymarket market resolved Yes after dispute rounds\n- Market rule allows \"definitive consensus of credible media reporting\"\n\n*For Defendant:*\n- No original livestream, VOD, transcript, or representative statement preserved\n- Times of India: \"no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no video confirming pregnancy, and no statement from Clavicular confirming it\"\n- Hindustan Times and Express Tribune preserve actual quoted words: \"I must have children...I will be a dad in the next few months\" — future aspirations, not existing pregnancy\n- Forbes extraction itself notes: \"market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes.\"\n- Forbes is incomplete snippets from a paywalled page, not full article with source chain\n\n**Analysis:**\nThe admitted record contains conflicting secondary reporting, not a \"definitive consensus.\" The preserved actual quotations describe a pregnancy contest proposal and future fatherhood desires, not confirmation of an existing partner pregnancy. The Forbes fragment lacks context and source chain. A final platform Yes resolution is not independent proof of the factual predicate. The primary source gaps are dispositive under preponderance.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_58387926b13243b3bb847e2a","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record lacks a preserved credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy. The only preserved actual quotations describe future fatherhood aspirations and a pregnancy contest proposal, not confirmation of an existing pregnancy. Forbes presents an incomplete fragment without source chain, while Times of India, Hindust